parts.markscheme:
_Award <marks>1 mark</marks> for each correct explanation, up to <marks>7 max</marks>_.

- recycling/re-use helps by preventing the release of non-biodegradable material/toxins into the soil;  
- reduction helps by reducing the quantity of non-biodegradable material/toxins produced/manufactured;  
promoting selective consumerism to avoid toxic products prevents them being present in domestic waste;  
- education/laws/fines that promote disposal of hazardous domestic waste in appropriate collecting facility will reduce their impact on soil fertility;  
- incineration may be helpful in breaking down non-biodegradable substances/organic toxins;  
…and the remaining mineral content can be used to enhance soil fertility;  
- landfills can limit the release of non-biodegradable material/toxins into soil with effective lining;  
- sorting of waste before entry to landfill can remove many toxic substances _eg_ batteries/fluorescent lamps/tyres/spray cans reducing risk to soil fertility through leakage;  
- deep well injection of hazardous wastes will prevent soil toxification;  
- all strategies that prevent release of toxins will preserve the soil fauna that contribute to fertility;  
- composting (although it does not breakdown non-biodegradable material/toxins) can compensate to some extent by providing soil nutrients that improve soil fertility.

Award <marks>1 mark</marks> for each of the following, <marks>2 marks max</marks>:

- the second law states that in any energy transfer, entropy increases / energy is degraded to a lower quality;
- much of the energy is dissipated as heat/thermal energy during respiration;
- heat energy cannot be reused by organisms and is lost to the environment;
- not all biomass is consumed or digested by the next trophic level (e.g., bones, fiber).

Award <marks>1 mark</marks> for each of the following, <marks>2 marks max</marks>:

- increased temperature can increase the rate of plant respiration ($$R$$);
- if respiration increases more than GPP, the NPP will decrease ($$NPP = GPP - R$$);
- very high temperatures may lead to water stress/closing of stomata, which would decrease GPP;
- conversely, in cold climates, a moderate increase may increase both GPP and NPP by extending the growing season.

Award <marks>1 mark max</marks> for any of the following:

- combustion of fossil fuels;
- volcanic eruptions / outgassing;
- diffusion from the ocean surface (ocean-to-atmosphere flux);
- animal/consumer respiration;
- forest fires (combustion of biomass).

Award <marks>1 mark max</marks> for any of the following:

- dissolving/diffusion into the oceans (carbonic acid formation);
- carbon capture and storage (human-engineered removal);
- weathering of silicate rocks (carbonation).

Award <marks>1 mark max</marks> for any of the following:

- intensive agriculture/monoculture results in soil nutrient depletion/reduction in organic matter;  
- deforestation for plantations leaves the soil bare contributing to soil erosion;  
- tillage/ploughing can leave soil prone to erosion;  
- excessive use of pesticides leading to soil toxification;  
- use of fertilizers increases soil productivity;

Award <marks>1 mark max</marks> for any of the following:

- use of fertilizers/leaching of nutrients can lead to eutrophication/algal blooms;  
- use of pesticides can lead to contamination of aquatic systems/death of non-target organisms/bioaccumulation;  
- over-abstraction of water for agriculture use may lead to low water levels (in rivers/lakes adversely affecting fish/aquatic species);  
- soil erosion into lakes/rivers could increase sedimentation/reduce water clarity;

_**Note**: For credit the cause and effect needs to be linked._

Award <marks>1 mark</marks> for any of the following:
- minerals (from weathered bedrock);
- rock fragments / parent material;
- volcanic ash;
- dissolved solutes in groundwater.

_Do not accept inputs from the atmosphere (e.g., precipitation) or the biosphere (e.g., leaf litter)_.

Award <marks>1 mark</marks> for any of the following:
- dead organic matter / humus;
- living soil organisms / soil biota (e.g., earthworms, fungi, bacteria);
- plant roots / seeds;
- chemical energy (stored in organic molecules).

_Do not accept "minerals" or "heat" as storages of energy (minerals are storages of matter; heat is a transient form of energy usually considered a flow or output)_.

Award <marks>1 mark</marks> for identifying the relevant property and <marks>1 mark</marks> for the explanation, up to <marks>2 marks max</marks>:
- Soil A has a very high sand content ($85\%$) which results in larger pore spaces / macropores;
- This leads to a high drainage rate / high permeability, which allows water to move rapidly through the profile and carry dissolved minerals/nutrients downward;
- Soil B has high clay content ($60\%$) and organic matter ($6\%$) which better adsorb/bind nutrients, whereas Soil A lacks these components to hold onto minerals.

Award <marks>1 mark</marks> for each distinct contribution described, up to <marks>2 marks max</marks>:
- decomposers (e.g., fungi/bacteria) break down organic matter into humus, which forms the distinct O and A horizons;
- earthworms/burrowing animals physically mix materials through the profile (biological mixing/translocation), moving organic matter down and minerals up;
- plant roots provide inputs of organic matter through root death and turnover within the subsoil layers;
- biological activity (e.g., root growth or animal tunneling) increases soil porosity, which facilitates the flow of water/air necessary for weathering processes;
- nitrogen-fixing bacteria transform atmospheric nitrogen into a form available in the soil, altering the chemical composition of the horizons.
